actions.comment:
Thanks for the detailed comparison with screenshots.

The Blazor `SKCanvasView` creates its raster surface with `SKAlphaType.Opaque`, while all other platform views (Windows Forms, WPF, etc.) use `SKAlphaType.Premul`. With `Opaque`, Skia doesn't guarantee meaningful alpha channel values in the pixel data, and when those bytes are transferred to the HTML Canvas via `putImageData`, the browser interprets them — producing the color distortion you're seeing.

Here's a workaround you can use now: explicitly clear the canvas with a solid background color at the start of your paint handler:

```csharp
void OnPaintSurface(SKPaintSurfaceEventArgs e)
{
    var canvas = e.Surface.Canvas;
    canvas.Clear(SKColors.White); // ensures all alpha bytes are defined
    // ... your drawing code with transparency
}
```

This ensures all pixels start with alpha=0xFF before any semi-transparent drawing occurs. Would you be able to confirm whether this resolves the color difference?
